Medical malpractice definition;
The “medical standard of care” is typically defined as the level and type of care that a reasonably competent and skilled health care professional, with a similar background and in the same medical community, would have provided under the circumstances that led to the alleged malpractice.
It certainly appears that Dr. Birx has committed malpractice and as such the medical board of the state(s) where she has a medical license to practice should be considering revoking her medical license.

Dear Editors of these coronavirus updates,

Please, please, please add the following past and current data for more accurate public understanding, most importantly the first one: 

1. Hospitalization rates; 
2. Positivity rates in percentages; 
3. Recovered case rates; 
4. Death rates in percentages;
5. Any other data which allows clear comparisons to New York and other previous COVID epicenters.

Especially without 1 and 2, the data may be misleading to readers. 

Thank you.

@NYTimes: I would appreciate some more precise information on "wearing a mask in public". Maybe you could ask Dr. Fauci or another person who actually knows something about epidemiology?  Here's why:  I try to exercise every day, outside, keeping at least 6-8 feet away from anyone else.  I choose my places of exercise carefully so I am able to keep my distance. 
While I exercise, I do not want to or can wear a mask - hard to do an aerobic workout with a mask on while dripping with sweat.  Now, I do religiously wear a mask anytime I am in closer proximity to others outside and, especially, anytime I have to share an indoor space with anyone else, regardless of distance.  And, by wearing a mask, I mean wearing a close-fitting mask without any valves, and one that covers both my mouth and nose entirely.  
Also, how about some information on the "masks" that have exhaust valves - widely worn and advertised, but aren't those borderline useless when it comes to protecting others?

